<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Day 6: The Image Proxy</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="challenge-page">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← Back to engagement</a>
    <div class="brand brand-sm">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="challenge-header">
      <h1>Day 6 · The Image Proxy</h1>
      <p class="desc">Skyway's customer-service tool fetches preview images server-side. It transparently adds an "internal" auth header. There's an internal admin endpoint that wants exactly that header. You see where this is going.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-box">
      <strong>The story.</strong> Customer service uses an image-preview tool. Paste any URL, the server fetches
      it and shows you the result. Performance-wise, this means the server makes the request, not your browser. When
      the server is the requestor, it adds whatever headers it wants. The internal admin endpoint at
      <code>/internal/admin-dump</code> checks for an <code>X-Service-Auth: …</code> header you don't know
      the value of. <strong>You don't need to know it.</strong> Make the proxy fetch the internal endpoint, and
      the proxy will add the header for you. That's SSRF.
    </div>

    <div class="challenge-content">
      <div class="fake-website">
        <div class="fake-navbar">
          <span>🛩️ Skyway · Image Preview Tool</span>
          <span>CS Console · Logout</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fake-body">
          <h2>Preview a URL</h2>
          <p>Paste any public image URL. Our server fetches it and returns the bytes.</p>
          <form method="GET" action="/challenge/6/preview" style="display:flex;gap:10px">
            <input name="url" placeholder="https://example.com/image.png" required class="flag-input" style="flex:1">
            <button class="submit-btn">Preview</button>
          </form>
          <p style="margin-top:14px;color:#888;font-size:0.9em">
            <em>Behind the scenes:</em> our service fetches the URL and adds an internal <code>X-Service-Auth</code> header so backend services trust the request.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="hint-box">
        <details>
          <summary class="hint-toggle">💡 What's actually broken here</summary>
          <p style="margin-top:8px;">The proxy doesn't validate that the URL points to an <em>external</em> service. Real SSRF attacks pivot from a public-facing tool like this into cloud metadata endpoints (<code>http://169.254.169.254/</code>), internal-only databases, admin panels. Anything the server can reach but the attacker normally can't.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="flag-form">
      <input type="text" class="flag-input" id="flagInput" placeholder="flag{...}" />
      <button class="submit-btn" onclick="submitFlag('ch6')">Submit finding</button>
    </div>
    <div class="result-msg" id="result"></div>
  </div>
  <script src="/js/submit.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
